            <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-myBlue mb-6">The "Retiree's Dilemma"</h2>
            
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                For 40 years, you're told to save in a 401(k) or IRA.
            </p>
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                The "experts" tell you to risk your money in the market to get growth.
            </p>
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Then, they tell you to move to "safe" bonds as you get older, where your money is eaten alive by inflation.
            </p>
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 font-bold leading-relaxed mb-6">
                This is the <strong>Retiree's Dilemma:</strong>
            </p>
            <ul class="list-none space-y-4 mb-6">
                <li class="text-xl leading-relaxed flex items-start">
                    <span class="text-myBlue font-bold mr-3">&#9656;</span>
                    <strong>OPTION A (RISK):</strong> Stay in the market and pray a crash doesn't wipe out 30% of your life savings.
                </li>
                <li class="text-xl leading-relaxed flex items-start">
                    <span class="text-myBlue font-bold mr-3">&#9656;</span>
                    <strong>OPTION B (INFLATION):</strong> Flee to "safety" and watch your purchasing power die a slow death.
                </li>
            </ul>

            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                What if this is a false choice?
                What if you could reject both options?
            </p>

            <!-- Insight Box -->
            <div class="bg-boxGray border-l-8 border-myBlue rounded-r-lg p-6 my-10 shadow-lg">
                <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-myBlue mb-3">The \$1,000 Insight:</p>
                <p class="text-xl text-black leading-relaxed">
                    Traditional retirement plans force you to choose between <strong class="text-myRed">Market Risk</strong> and <strong class="text-myRed">Inflation Risk</strong>. This guide shows you the third option they don't talk about.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section: Catastrophic Risk -->
        <section class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-myBlue mb-6">The Catastrophic Risk No One Talks About</h2>
            
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                This is the most important concept a retiree can understand.
            </p>
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                It's called <strong>Sequence of Returns Risk</strong>.
            </p>
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                It's a simple concept: <strong>WHEN your returns happen matters more than your <em>average</em> return.</strong>
            </p>
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Let's look at two retirees. Both have \$1,000,000. Both need to withdraw \$50,000 (5%) per year to live.
            </p>
            <ul class="list-none space-y-4 mb-6">
                <li class="text-xl leading-relaxed flex items-start">
                    <span class="text-myBlue font-bold mr-3">&#9656;</span>
                    <strong>Retiree A (Traditional 60/40 Plan):</strong> Retires into a bear market.
                </li>
                <li class="text-xl leading-relaxed flex items-start">
                    <span class="text-myBlue font-bold mr-3">&#9656;</span>
                    <strong>Retiree B (0% Floor Strategy):</strong> Retires into the <em>exact same</em> bear market.
                </li>
            </ul>

            <!-- Table 1 -->
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-2">Retiree A (Traditional 60/40)*</p>
            <div class="overflow-x-auto shadow-md rounded-lg">
